<methodology slug="value-proposition-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>user-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Design a compelling value proposition using the Value Proposition Canvas. Map customer jobs, pains, gains against product features to achieve fit and clarify why customers choose you.</summary>
    <category>research</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>value-proposition</tag>
      <tag>positioning</tag>
      <tag>canvas</tag>
      <tag>strategy</tag>
      <tag>customer-research</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Value Proposition Design</title>
    <summary>Products fail because they don't clearly articulate why someone should buy. Value Proposition Design is a systematic process for designing a compelling value proposition using the Value Proposition Canvas from Strategyzer. The canvas maps customer jobs, pains, and gains against product features, pain relievers, and gain creators to achieve fit and articulate why customers should choose you over alternatives.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>A value proposition is the promise of value to be delivered. It answers: "Why should I choose you over the alternatives?" Without a systematic process, teams default to feature lists instead of benefits, copy the same messaging as competitors, fail to articulate value to target audiences, or design products with poor fit between offer and customer needs. The Value Proposition Canvas provides the structure to avoid these failures.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch positioning: before writing landing page copy or running ads</item>
        <item>After user research: translating raw interview findings into a structured Jobs/Pains/Gains canvas</item>
        <item>Competitive repositioning: when a new competitor enters and the current pitch no longer differentiates</item>
        <item>Investor pitch prep: the value proposition canvas maps directly to the "Why us?" slide</item>
        <item>Feature prioritization: pain relievers and gain creators ranked by severity guide the roadmap</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before any user research — without customer evidence, the canvas is self-flattering fiction</item>
        <item>When the product is pivoting mid-development and the customer segment has not been re-validated</item>
        <item>As a one-time exercise — value propositions require iteration as the market responds; a canvas frozen at launch is a liability</item>
        <item>When the team cannot agree on the primary customer segment — resolve segmentation first</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="value-proposition-canvas">
      <p>The Value Proposition Canvas from Strategyzer maps two halves: Customer Profile and Value Map. The Customer Profile contains three columns (Jobs, Pains, Gains); the Value Map contains three columns (Products &amp; Services, Pain Relievers, Gain Creators). Fit is achieved when the Value Map directly addresses the Customer Profile.</p>
      <term name="jobs">What the customer is trying to get done. Jobs fall into three categories: Functional (file taxes, manage projects), Emotional (feel in control, reduce stress), Social (look competent, gain status). For each job, note when it arises, how often, and what outcome is desired.</term>
      <term name="pains">What blocks or frustrates the customer from accomplishing their jobs. Pain categories include Undesired outcomes (takes too long, costs too much), Obstacles (can't figure it out, no budget), Risks (might fail, could lose data). Score each pain on severity: Extreme (must solve), Moderate (should solve), Minor (nice to solve).</term>
      <term name="gains">What the customer wants to achieve or would love to have. Gain categories include Required (minimum expectation), Expected (standard for category), Desired (would love to have), Unexpected (delightful surprise). Focus on Expected and Desired gains.</term>
      <term name="pain-relievers">How the product eliminates or reduces a customer pain. For each pain, answer: What specific feature addresses it? How significantly does it help? Relief level: Partial or Complete.</term>
      <term name="gain-creators">How the product creates a desired customer gain. For each gain, answer: What outcomes does it produce? How does it exceed expectations? Delight level: Expected or Surprising.</term>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Populate the Customer Profile before the Value Map — working in the opposite direction produces self-serving analysis.</statement>
        <rationale>Value-first mapping leads to confirmation bias; customer-first mapping forces the product to respond to real needs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Rank pains by severity before mapping pain relievers; a product that addresses 5 minor pains but ignores the one extreme pain has poor fit.</statement>
        <rationale>Resource constraint forces prioritization; addressing severity ensures the product solves the highest-impact problem.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use verbatim customer language in the canvas — "takes forever to sync" is more actionable than "slow synchronization".</statement>
        <rationale>Direct language preserves emotional intensity and avoids abstract paraphrasing that loses signal.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="value-proposition-statement">
      <p>A value proposition statement answers "Why should I choose you?" using a formula: For [target customer] Who [has this job/need] [Product name] is a [category] That [key benefit] Unlike [alternative] We [key differentiator].</p>
      <example type="good" title="Newsletter platform statement">
        <text>For independent writers Who want to grow and monetize their newsletter NewsletterKit is an email platform That stays affordable as you scale Unlike Substack or ConvertKit We charge flat fees, not per-subscriber</text>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Freelance project management statement">
        <text>For solo freelancers Who juggle multiple client projects FreelanceOS is project management That includes client portals and invoicing Unlike Asana or Notion Everything you need is in one simple tool</text>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Write 3 value proposition statement variants using the For/Who/Is/That/Unlike/We formula. Each variant should emphasize a different differentiator. Avoid marketing superlatives ("best", "easiest", "most powerful").</statement>
        <rationale>Multiple variants surface different positioning angles; superlatives are legally and emotionally risky.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Test the value proposition statement with 5 target customers before using it in ads; if they cannot identify themselves in "For [target customer]", the segment is too narrow or the language is off.</statement>
        <rationale>Customer feedback validates the segment definition and language clarity before investment.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="fit-assessment">
      <p>Fit is achieved across three levels: Problem-Solution Fit (you address real jobs/pains/gains), Product-Market Fit (customers pay and keep using), Business Model Fit (profitable and scalable). Test fit by: Do customers recognize the pains you describe? Do they value the gains you promise? Will they pay for your solution?</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Map every gain creator and pain reliever to a specific product feature — if you cannot name the feature, the claim is aspirational, not a real proposition.</statement>
        <rationale>Unmapped claims are undeliverable and create customer disappointment at launch.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Revisit the canvas after 90 days of shipping — pains that seemed extreme at discovery may have been solved by workarounds, revealing new priorities.</statement>
        <rationale>Market response shifts customer priorities; stale canvases drive feature bloat instead of impact.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Claude subagents can generate a first-draft Value Proposition Canvas from a product description and available user research, produce the value proposition statement, and compare it against 2-3 listed competitors. The most reliable agent task is synthesizing interview findings into the Jobs/Pains/Gains structure — agent input should be raw quotes, not a summary. The Fit Assessment must be validated by a human with market context; agents will rate fit optimistically. Recommended subagents: faion-idea-generator-agent (generates VP canvas, VP statement, competitor positioning table); faion-research-agent (mode: pains, sources pain data from public channels to populate the Customer Profile).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <prompt purpose="value-canvas"><![CDATA[
Fill the Value Proposition Canvas for this product using the customer interview quotes below.
For each element, cite the specific quote that supports it.
Do NOT invent pains or gains not evidenced in the quotes.

Product: {description}
Target customer: {segment}
Interview quotes:
{quotes}

Output format:
- Customer Jobs: [list with evidence]
- Customer Pains: [list with severity: Extreme/Moderate/Minor, and evidence]
- Customer Gains: [list with type: Required/Expected/Desired, and evidence]
- Pain Relievers: [how product addresses each pain]
- Gain Creators: [how product creates each gain]
- Fit score: [1-5 per dimension, with reason]
]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="value-statement"><![CDATA[
Write 3 value proposition statement variants using the For/Who/Is/That/Unlike/We formula.
Each variant should emphasize a different differentiator.
Avoid marketing superlatives ("best", "easiest", "most powerful").

Customer: {segment}
Top pain: {pain}
Top gain: {gain}
Key differentiators vs. {competitor}: {differentiators}
]]></prompt>
    </section>
    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>CLI tools: strategyzer web app (official VP Canvas tool; export to PDF/PNG); miro API (create VP canvas boards programmatically); notion API (store canvas as structured database); figma API (export VP canvas diagrams from template).</p>
      <p>Services: Strategyzer (SaaS, No, gold standard for the canvas, no API); Miro (SaaS, Partial, REST API for board creation, shapes and stickies supported); Notion (SaaS, Yes, best for structured data storage of canvas elements); Typeform (SaaS, Yes, customer survey to surface pains and gains at scale); Hotjar (SaaS, Partial, open-text survey responses for pain mining).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Populate the Customer Profile before the Value Map — working in the opposite direction produces self-serving analysis. Rank pains by severity before mapping pain relievers; a product that addresses 5 minor pains but ignores the one extreme pain has poor fit. Use verbatim customer language in the canvas — "takes forever to sync" is more actionable than "slow synchronization". Test the value proposition statement with 5 target customers before using it in ads; if they cannot identify themselves in "For [target customer]", the segment is too narrow or the language is off. Revisit the canvas after 90 days of shipping — pains that seemed extreme at discovery may have been solved by workarounds, revealing new priorities. Map every gain creator and pain reliever to a specific product feature — if you cannot name the feature, the claim is aspirational, not a real proposition.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Feature-focused messaging instead of benefit-focused.</description>
        <reason>Features describe what the product does; benefits describe what the customer gets. "Cloud storage" is a feature; "never lose your files again" is a benefit.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generic value proposition that applies to all competitors.</description>
        <reason>Same messaging as 10 competitors means no differentiation. Specificity requires competitive research and unique positioning.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ignoring competition in the canvas.</description>
        <reason>Without competitive context, "fit" is relative to nothing. Position against alternatives.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming you know the pains without validation.</description>
        <reason>Self-flattering fiction happens when customer research is skipped. Canvas without interviews produces a list of features, not a value proposition.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Too many benefits claimed.</description>
        <reason>Cognitive overload; customers remember at most 3 claims. Prioritize.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents filling the canvas without real user research data will hallucinate plausible-sounding pains that do not reflect the actual market.</description>
        <reason>LLMs cannot distinguish genuine market pain from hypothetical scenarios. Always provide raw interview quotes as input, not summaries.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>VP statement generation tends to be generic when the differentiator is not explicitly named; force the agent to name the specific feature that makes the claim true.</description>
        <reason>Without specificity, the statement could apply to any competitor. Example: "best support" is generic; "support in under 2 hours" is specific.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Fit assessment by agents is optimistic by default; require the agent to identify the one extreme pain that the product does NOT address well.</description>
        <reason>Agents tend to rate fit as "Strong" across the board. Forcing the agent to name the gap reveals honesty about trade-offs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Gain" and "feature" are conflated by agents — a gain is a customer outcome ("feel in control"), not a product feature ("dashboard").</description>
        <reason>Without the distinction, agents mix product description with customer value. Gain = outcome; feature = mechanism.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents filling pains without interview data will anchor on the most common SaaS pains (pricing, onboarding, support) regardless of the actual product — always provide raw quotes as input.</description>
        <reason>Without constraints, agents generate plausible but hypothetical pains. Raw quotes ground analysis in reality.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>VP statement generation tends to be generic when the differentiator is not explicitly named; force the agent to name the specific feature that makes the claim true.</description>
        <reason>Without specificity, the statement could apply to any competitor. Example: "best support" is generic; "support in under 2 hours" is specific.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Fit assessment by agents is optimistic by default; require the agent to identify the one extreme pain that the product does NOT address well.</description>
        <reason>Agents tend to rate fit as "Strong" across the board. Forcing the agent to name the gap reveals honesty about trade-offs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Human checkpoint required before VP statement is used in marketing — agents cannot evaluate whether the claim is legally defensible or culturally appropriate.</description>
        <reason>LLMs can produce statements that sound compelling but violate FTC guidelines or offend target audience. Human review is non-negotiable.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="inline-fit-scorer">
      <p>Python helper to score fit between customer profile and value map</p>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def score_fit(pains: list[dict], pain_relievers: list[dict],
              gains: list[dict], gain_creators: list[dict]) -> dict:
    """
    Each pain/gain: {"label": str, "severity": "Extreme"|"Moderate"|"Minor"}
    Each reliever/creator: {"addresses": str, "relief_level": "Complete"|"Partial"}
    """
    addressed_pains = {r["addresses"] for r in pain_relievers}
    addressed_gains = {c["addresses"] for c in gain_creators}

    extreme_pains = [p for p in pains if p["severity"] == "Extreme"]
    covered_extreme = [p for p in extreme_pains if p["label"] in addressed_pains]

    required_gains = [g for g in gains if g["severity"] == "Required"]
    covered_required = [g for g in required_gains if g["label"] in addressed_gains]

    return {
        "pain_coverage": len(addressed_pains) / max(len(pains), 1),
        "extreme_pain_coverage": len(covered_extreme) / max(len(extreme_pains), 1),
        "required_gain_coverage": len(covered_required) / max(len(required_gains), 1),
        "overall_fit": "Strong" if len(covered_extreme) == len(extreme_pains) else "Partial",
    }
]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="value-proposition-canvas-definition">
      <p>The Value Proposition Canvas has two halves separated by the "fit" dimension. The Customer Profile side (left) contains Jobs, Pains, and Gains. The Value Map side (right) contains Products &amp; Services, Pain Relievers, and Gain Creators. Jobs are what customers are trying to accomplish: functional (file taxes, manage projects), emotional (feel in control, reduce stress), or social (look competent, gain status). Pains are obstacles, undesired outcomes, or risks. Gains are outcomes the customer would like to achieve, categorized as Required (minimum), Expected (standard), Desired (aspirational), or Unexpected (delightful). The pain relievers show how the product solves each pain; gain creators show how the product creates desired outcomes. Fit is achieved when the Value Map comprehensively addresses the Customer Profile — high fit means every extreme pain is relieved and every required gain is created. The canvas is a snapshot; it does not model how gains and pains shift as customers mature. Agents filling the canvas without real user research data will hallucinate plausible-sounding pains that do not reflect the actual market. "Fit" assessment is qualitative — the canvas does not calculate fit, it prompts structured thinking. The formula-based value proposition statement (For/Who/Is/That/Unlike/We) produces mechanical copy; requires copywriter refinement for actual marketing use. Pain severity ratings are subjective without explicit scoring methodology; teams disagree on what "extreme" means.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="process-steps">
      <step>Map Customer Jobs: Functional, Emotional, Social. For each job, note when it arises, frequency, and desired outcome.</step>
      <step>Identify Pains: Undesired outcomes, Obstacles, Risks. Score each on severity (Extreme/Moderate/Minor) and frequency (Daily/Weekly/Monthly/Annual).</step>
      <step>Discover Gains: Required, Expected, Desired, Unexpected. Focus on Expected and Desired.</step>
      <step>Design Pain Relievers: For each pain, name the specific feature that addresses it and relief level (Partial/Complete).</step>
      <step>Create Gain Creators: For each gain, name the specific feature that creates it and delight level (Expected/Surprising).</step>
      <step>Achieve Fit: Check if the Value Map (products, pain relievers, gain creators) fully addresses the Customer Profile (jobs, pains, gains).</step>
      <step>Write Value Proposition Statement: Using the For/Who/Is/That/Unlike/We formula, write 3 variants.</step>
      <step>Test with Customers: Share the statement with 5 target customers. If they don't recognize themselves in "For [target customer]", iterate.</step>
    </section>
